Given two strings s and t, return true if t is an anagram of s, and false otherwise.
Example 1:
Input: s = "anagram", t = "nagaram"
Output: true

Example 2:
Input: s = "rat", t = "car"
Output: false


class Solution {
    public boolean isAnagram(String s, String t) {
        if(s.length()!=t.length())  return false;
        int[] freq=new int[26];
        Arrays.fill(freq,0);
        for(int i=0;i<s.length();i++)
            freq[s.charAt(i)-'a']++;
        for(int i=0;i<t.length();i++)
            freq[t.charAt(i)-'a']--;
        for(int i=0;i<freq.length;i++)
            if(freq[i]!=0)
                return false;
        return true;
    }
}



import java.util.HashMap;

class Solution {
    public boolean isAnagram(String s, String t) {
        if (s.length() != t.length()) return false;

        HashMap<Character, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();

        // Count frequencies from string s
        for (char c : s.toCharArray()) 
            map.put(c, map.getOrDefault(c, 0) + 1);

        // Subtract frequencies using string t
        for (char c : t.toCharArray()) {
            if (!map.containsKey(c)) return false;
            map.put(c, map.get(c) - 1);
            if (map.get(c) == 0) 
                map.remove(c); // cleanup to keep map small
        }

        // If map is empty, all counts matched
        return map.isEmpty();
    }
}


System.out.println(new Solution().isAnagram("déjà", "jadé")); // true
System.out.println(new Solution().isAnagram("你好", "好你"));   // true
System.out.println(new Solution().isAnagram("rat", "car"));   // false

Your array‑based solution is best for lowercase English letters → O(n) time, O(1) space.
The HashMap solution generalizes to Unicode → O(n) time, O(k) space.
Both are efficient and cover different use cases.
